  "explanations": [
    {
      "text": "The particle は marks the topic of a sentence — what the sentence is about. It comes right after the noun you want to talk about. Think of it as saying \"As for X, ...\" For example, 私は学生です literally means \"As for me, (I) am a student.\"",
      "title": "What は does"
    },
    {
      "text": "Even though this particle is written with the hiragana は (normally read \"ha\"), when used as the topic marker it is pronounced \"wa.\" The spelling never changes — always write は, not わ, when marking a topic.",
      "title": "Spelling vs. pronunciation"
    },
    {
      "text": "To use は, place it directly after the noun that is your topic. The rest of the sentence then says something about that topic. Typical patterns look like [Noun]は[Noun]です or [Noun]は[Adjective]です.",
      "title": "How to use it"
    }
  ],
  "questions": [
