    {
      "text": "In a German main clause, the conjugated verb must always be the second element. \"Second\" doesn't mean the second word — it means the second sentence position. The first position can be a subject, a time expression, a place, or any other phrase, but the very next slot belongs to the verb.",
      "title": "The verb goes in position two"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you put something other than the subject in position one (like a time phrase), the subject is pushed to position three, right after the verb. This is different from English, where the subject usually stays before the verb. So \"Tomorrow I go\" becomes Morgen gehe ich — verb before subject.",
      "title": "What happens to the subject"
    }
  ],
